      "id": 1,
      "text": "North Wantagh began as the 1666 Quaker settlement called Jerusalem, a biblical name chosen by early settlers.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2,
        22
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/north_wantagh_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The South Shore Railroad’s 1867 arrival sparked rapid growth, leading to the depot’s renaming and the wider adoption of the name Wantagh by 1891.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/north_wantagh_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "North Wantagh represents the northern portion of the original Jerusalem tract, now integrated into the Town of Hempstead’s administrative framework.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/north_wantagh_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Locals call Wantagh the “Gateway to Jones Beach,” highlighting its role as the first Long Island stop before the famed beach.",
